# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lambda-cube
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] In mathematical logic and computer science, the **calculus of constructions** (**CoC**) is a type theory created by Thierry Coquand.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] It can serve as both a typed programming language and as constructive foundation for mathematics.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] For this second reason, the CoC and its variants have been the basis for Rocq and other proof assistants.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] Some of its variants include the calculus of inductive constructions (which adds inductive types), the calculus of (co)inductive constructions (which adds coinduction), and the predicative calculus of inductive constructions (which removes some impredicativity).
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The CoC is a higher-order typed lambda calculus, initially developed by Thierry Coquand.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] It is well known for being at the top of Barendregt's lambda cube.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] It is possible within CoC to define functions from terms to terms, terms to types, types to types, and from types to terms.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The CoC is strongly normalizing, and hence consistent.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The CoC has been developed alongside the Rocq proof assistant.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] As features were added (or possible liabilities removed) to the theory, they became available in Rocq.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] Variants of the CoC are used in other proof assistants, such as Matita and Lean.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The calculus of constructions can be considered an extension of the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The Curry–Howard isomorphism associates a term in the simply typed lambda calculus with each natural-deduction proof in intuitionistic propositional logic.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The calculus of constructions extends this isomorphism to proofs in the full intuitionistic predicate calculus, which includes proofs of quantified statements (which we will also call "propositions").
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] 5. $\mathbf {T}$ itself, which is the type of large types.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] As with the untyped lambda calculus, the calculus of constructions uses a basic notion of equivalence of terms, known as $\beta$ -equivalence.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The valid judgments for the calculus of constructions are derivable from a set of inference rules.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] In the following, we use $\Gamma$ to mean a sequence of type assignments $x_{1}:A_{1},x_{2}:A_{2},\ldots$ ; $A,B,C,D$ to mean terms; and $K,L$ to mean either $\mathbf {P}$ or $\mathbf {T}$ .
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] We shall write $B[x:=N]$ to mean the result of substituting the term N for the free variable x in the term B .
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] The calculus of constructions has very few basic operators: the only logical operator for forming propositions is $\forall$ .
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] Booleans and Naturals are defined in the same way as in Church encoding.
[src:lambda-cube/calculus-of-constructions] However, added problems arise from propositional extensionality and proof irrelevance.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] Barendregt studied mathematical logic at Utrecht University, obtaining his master's degree in 1968 and his PhD in 1971, both *cum laude*, under Dirk van Dalen and Georg Kreisel.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] After a postdoctoral position at Stanford University, he taught at Utrecht University.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] Since 1986, Barendregt has taught at Radboud University Nijmegen, where he now holds the Chair of Foundations of Mathematics and Computer Science.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] His research group works on Constructive Interactive Mathematics.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] He is also adjunct professor at Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, US.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] He has been a visiting scholar at Darmstadt, ETH Zürich, Siena, and Kyoto.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] Barendregt was elected a member of Academia Europaea in 1992.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] In 1997 Barendregt was elected member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] On 6 February 2003 Barendregt was awarded the Spinozapremie for 2002, the highest scientific award in the Netherlands.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] In 2002 he was knighted in the Orde van de Nederlandse Leeuw.
[src:lambda-cube/henk-barendregt] Barendregt received an honorary doctorate from Heriot-Watt University in 2015.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In mathematical logic and type theory, the **λ-cube** (also written **lambda cube**) is a framework introduced by Henk Barendregt to investigate the different dimensions in which the calculus of constructions is a generalization of the simply typed λ-calculus.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Each dimension of the cube corresponds to a new kind of dependency between terms and types.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Here, "dependency" refers to the capacity of a term or type to bind a term or type.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The different ways to combine these three dimensions yield the 8 vertices of the cube, each corresponding to a different kind of typed system.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The λ-cube can be generalized into the concept of a pure type system.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The simplest system found in the λ-cube is the simply typed lambda calculus, also called λ→.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The terms beginning with a $\Lambda$ are called polymorphic, as they can be applied to different types to get different functions, similarly to polymorphic functions in ML-like languages.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] meaning it can take an argument of any type `'a` and return an element of that type.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] This type corresponds in λ2 to the type $\Pi \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In System F ${\underline {\omega }}$ a construction is introduced to supply *types that depend on other types*.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] This is called a type constructor and provides a way to build "a function with a type as a *value*".
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] An example of such a type constructor is the type of binary trees with leaves labeled by data of a given type A : ${\mathsf {TREE}}:=\lambda A:*.\Pi B.(A\to B)\to (B\to B\to B)\to B$ , where " $A:*$ " informally means " A is a type".
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] This is a function that takes a type parameter A as an argument and returns the type of ${\mathsf {TREE}}$ s of values of type A .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In concrete programming, this feature corresponds to the ability to define type constructors inside the language, rather than considering them as primitives.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] This type constructor can be applied to other types to obtain new types.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] System F ${\underline {\omega }}$ is generally not used on its own, but is useful to isolate the independent feature of type constructors.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In the λP system, also named λΠ, which is closely related to the LF Logical Framework, one has so called dependent types.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] These are *types that are allowed to depend on terms*.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The new type constructor $\Pi$ corresponds via the Curry-Howard isomorphism to a universal quantifier, and the system λP as a whole corresponds to first-order logic with implication as only connective.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] An example of these dependent types in concrete programming is the type of vectors on a certain length: the length is a term, on which the type depends.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] System Fω combines both the $\Lambda$ constructor of System F and the type constructors from System F ${\underline {\omega }}$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Thus System Fω provides both *terms that depend on types* and *types that depend on types*.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In the calculus of constructions, denoted as λC in the cube or as λPω, these four features cohabit, so that both types and terms can depend on types and terms.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The clear border that exists in λ→ between terms and types is somewhat abolished, as all types except the universal $\square$ are themselves terms with a type.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] As for all systems based upon the simply typed lambda calculus, all systems in the cube are given in two steps: first, raw terms, together with a notion of β-reduction, and then typing rules that allow to type those terms.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The set of sorts is defined as $S:=\{*,\square \}$ , sorts are represented with the letter s .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] There is also a set V of variables, represented by the letters $x,y,\dots$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] and $A\to B$ denoting $\Pi x:A.B$ when x does not occur free in B .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The notion of β-reduction is common to all systems in the cube.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] A typical derivation that can be obtained is ${\displaystyle \alpha$ or with the arrow shortcut ${\displaystyle \alpha$ closely resembling the identity (of type ${\textstyle \alpha }$ ) of the usual λ→.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Note that all types used must appear in the context, because the only derivation that can be done in an empty context is ${\textstyle \vdash *:\square }$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The computing power is quite weak, it corresponds to the extended polynomials (polynomials together with a conditional operator).
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In λ2, such terms can be obtained as ${\displaystyle \vdash (\lambda \beta$ with ${\textstyle \bot =\Pi \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] If one reads ${\textstyle \Pi }$ as a universal quantification, via the Curry-Howard isomorphism, this can be seen as a proof of the principle of explosion.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In general, λ2 adds the possibility to have impredicative types such as ${\textstyle \bot }$ , that is terms quantifying over all types including themselves.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The polymorphism also allows the construction of functions that were not constructible in λ→.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] More precisely, the functions definable in λ2 are those provably total in second-order Peano arithmetic.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In particular, all primitive recursive functions are definable.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In λP, the ability to have types depending on terms means one can express logical predicates.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] For instance, the following is derivable: ${\displaystyle {\begin{array}{l}\alpha$ which corresponds, via the Curry-Howard isomorphism, to a proof of $(\forall x:A,Px\to Q)\to (\forall x:A,Px)\to Q$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] From the computational point of view, however, having dependent types does not enhance computational power, only the possibility to express more precise type properties.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The conversion rule is strongly needed when dealing with dependent types, because it allows to perform computation on the terms in the type.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] For instance, if one has $\Gamma \vdash A:P((\lambda x.x)y)$ and $\Gamma \vdash B:\Pi x:P(y).C$ , one needs to apply the conversion rule to obtain $\Gamma \vdash A:P(y)$ to be able to type $\Gamma \vdash BA:C$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In λω, the following operator ${\displaystyle AND:=\lambda \alpha$ is definable, that is $\vdash AND:*\to *\to *$ .
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The derivation ${\displaystyle \alpha$ can be obtained already in λ2, however the polymorphic ${\textstyle AND}$ can only be defined if the rule ${\textstyle (\square ,*)}$ is also present.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] From a computing point of view, λω is extremely strong, and has been considered as a basis for programming languages.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The calculus of constructions has both the predicate expressiveness of λP and the computational power of λω, hence why λC is also called λPω, so it is very powerful, both on the logical side and on the computational side.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The system Automath is similar to λ2 from a logical point of view.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The ML-like languages, from a typing point of view, lie somewhere between λ→ and λ2, as they admit a restricted kind of polymorphic types, that is the types in prenex normal form.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] However, because they feature some recursion operators, their computing power is greater than that of λ2.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The Coq system is based on an extension of λC with a linear hierarchy of universes, rather than only one untypable ${\textstyle \square }$ , and the ability to construct inductive types.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Pure type systems can be seen as a generalization of the cube, with an arbitrary set of sorts, axiom, product and abstraction rules.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] All the logics are implicative (i.e. the only connectives are ${\textstyle \to }$ and ${\textstyle \forall }$ ); however, one can define other connectives such as $\wedge$ or $\neg$ in an impredicative way in second and higher order logics.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In the weak higher order logics, there are variables for higher order predicates, but no quantification on those can be done.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] All of these can be proven on generic pure type systems.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Any term well-typed in a system of the cube is strongly normalizing, although this property is not common to all pure type systems.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] No system in the cube is Turing complete.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Subtyping however is not represented in the cube, even though systems like $F_{<:}^{\omega }$ , known as higher-order bounded quantification, which combines subtyping and polymorphism are of practical interest, and can be further generalized to bounded type operators.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] Further extensions to $F_{<:}^{\omega }$ allow the definition of purely functional objects; these systems were generally developed after the lambda cube paper was published.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The idea of the cube is due to the mathematician Henk Barendregt (1991).
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] The framework of pure type systems generalizes the lambda cube in the sense that all corners of the cube, as well as many other systems can be represented as instances of this general framework.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] This framework predates the lambda cube by a couple of years.
[src:lambda-cube/lambda-cube] In his 1991 paper, Barendregt also defines the corners of the cube in this framework.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Is every weakly normalizing pure type system also strongly normalizing?
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] In the branches of mathematical logic known as proof theory and type theory, a **pure type system** (**PTS**), previously known as a **generalized type system** (**GTS**), is a form of typed lambda calculus that allows an arbitrary number of sorts and dependencies between any of these.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] The framework can be seen as a generalisation of Barendregt's lambda cube, in the sense that all corners of the cube can be represented as instances of a PTS with just two sorts.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] In fact, Barendregt (1991) framed his cube in this setting.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Pure type systems may obscure the distinction between *types* and *terms* and collapse the type hierarchy, as is the case with the calculus of constructions, but this is not generally the case, e.g. the simply typed lambda calculus allows only terms to depend on terms.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Pure type systems were independently introduced by Stefano Berardi (1988) and Jan Terlouw (1989).
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Barendregt discussed them at length in his subsequent papers.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] In his PhD thesis, Berardi defined a cube of constructive logics akin to the lambda cube (these specifications are non-dependent).
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] A modification of this cube was later called the L-cube by Herman Geuvers, who in his PhD thesis extended the Curry–Howard correspondence to this setting.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Barthe and others defined *classical pure type systems* (CPTS) by adding a double negation operator.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Similarly, in 1998, Tijn Borghuis introduced *modal pure type systems* (MPTS).
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Roorda has discussed the application of pure type systems to functional programming; and Roorda and Jeuring have proposed a programming language based on pure type systems.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] The systems from the lambda cube are all known to be strongly normalizing.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] Pure type systems in general need not be, for example System U from **Girard's paradox** is not.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] It is a major open problem in the field whether this is always the case, i.e. whether a (weakly) normalizing PTS always has the strong normalization property.
[src:lambda-cube/pure-type-system] This is known as the Barendregt–Geuvers–Klop conjecture (named after Henk Barendregt, Herman Geuvers, and Jan Willem Klop).
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Whereas simply typed lambda calculus has variables ranging over terms, and binders for them, System F additionally has variables ranging over *types*, and binders for them.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The upper-case $\Lambda$ is traditionally used to denote type-level functions, as opposed to the lower-case $\lambda$ which is used for value-level functions.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] As a term rewriting system, System F is strongly normalizing.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] However, type inference in System F (without explicit type annotations) is undecidable.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Under the Curry–Howard isomorphism, System F corresponds to second-order propositional intuitionistic logic.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] System F can be seen as part of the lambda cube, together with even more expressive typed lambda calculi, including those with dependent types.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] According to Girard, the "F" in *System F* was picked by chance.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] where $\sigma ,\tau$ are types, $\alpha$ is a type variable, and $\alpha ~{\text{type}}$ in the context indicates that $\alpha$ is bound.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The first rule is that of application, and the second is that of abstraction.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ type is defined as: $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha \to \alpha$ , where $\alpha$ is a type variable.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] (Note that the above two functions require *three* — not two — arguments.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The latter two should be lambda expressions, but the first one should be a type.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] This fact is reflected in the fact that the type of these expressions is $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha \to \alpha$ ; the universal quantifier binding the α corresponds to the Λ binding the alpha in the lambda expression itself.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Also, note that ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ is a convenient shorthand for $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to \alpha \to \alpha$ , but it is not a symbol of System F itself, but rather a "meta-symbol".
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Note that in the definitions above, ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ is a type argument to x , specifying that the other two parameters that are given to x are of type ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ .
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] As in Church encodings, there is no need for an IFTHENELSE function as one can just use raw ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ -typed terms as decision functions.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] A *predicate* is a function which returns a ${\mathsf {Boolean}}$ -typed value.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] System F allows recursive constructions to be embedded in a natural manner, related to that in Martin-Löf's type theory.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Abstract structures (S) are created using *constructors*.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Recursivity is manifested when S itself appears within one of the types $K_{i}$ .
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The System F type corresponding to this structure is $\forall \alpha .\alpha \to (\alpha \to \alpha )\to \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] If we reverse the order of the curried arguments (*i.e.,* $\forall \alpha .(\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow \alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ ), then the Church numeral for n is a function that takes a function f as argument and returns the nth power of f.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] That is to say, a Church numeral is a higher-order function – it takes a single-argument function f, and returns another single-argument function.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The version of System F used in this article is as an explicitly typed, or Church-style, calculus.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] The typing information contained in λ-terms makes type-checking straightforward.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Joe Wells (1994) settled an "embarrassing open problem" by proving that type checking is undecidable for a Curry-style variant of System F, that is, one that lacks explicit typing annotations.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Wells's result implies that type inference for System F is impossible.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] A restriction of System F known as "Hindley–Milner", or simply "HM", does have an easy type inference algorithm and is used for many statically typed functional programming languages such as Haskell 98 and the ML family.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Over time, as the restrictions of HM-style type systems have become apparent, languages have steadily moved to more expressive logics for their type systems.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] GHC, a Haskell compiler, goes beyond HM (as of 2008) and uses System F extended with non-syntactic type equality; non-HM features in OCaml's type system include GADT.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] In second-order intuitionistic logic, the second-order polymorphic lambda calculus (F2) was discovered by Girard (1972) and independently by Reynolds (1974).
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Girard proved the *representation theorem*: that in second-order intuitionistic predicate logic (P2), functions from the natural numbers to the natural numbers that can be proved total, form a projection from P2 into F2.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Reynolds proved the *abstraction theorem*: that every term in F2 satisfies a logical relation, which can be embedded into the logical relations P2.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Reynolds proved that a Girard projection followed by a Reynolds embedding form the identity, i.e., the **Girard–Reynolds isomorphism**.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] While System F corresponds to the first axis of Barendregt's lambda cube, **System Fω** or the **higher-order polymorphic lambda calculus** combines the first axis (polymorphism) with the second axis (type operators); it is a different, more complex system.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] That is, Fω is the system which allows functions from types to types where the argument (and result) may be of any order.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] Note that although Fω places no restrictions on the *order* of the arguments in these mappings, it does restrict the *universe* of the arguments for these mappings: they must be types rather than values.
[src:lambda-cube/system-f-omega] System Fω does not permit mappings from values to types (dependent types), though it does permit mappings from values to values ( $\lambda$ abstraction), mappings from types to values ( $\Lambda$ abstraction), and mappings from types to types ( $\lambda$ abstraction at the level of types).
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] In mathematics and computer science, a **typed lambda calculus** is a typed formalism that uses the lambda symbol ( $\lambda$ ) to denote anonymous function abstraction.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] In this context, types are usually objects of a syntactic nature that are assigned to lambda terms; the exact nature of a type depends on the calculus considered (see kinds below).
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] From a certain point of view, typed lambda calculi can be seen as refinements of the untyped lambda calculus, but from another point of view, they can also be considered the more fundamental theory and *untyped lambda calculus* a special case with only one type.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi are foundational programming languages and are the base of typed functional programming languages such as ML and Haskell and, more indirectly, typed imperative programming languages.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi play an important role in the design of type systems for programming languages; here, typability usually captures desirable properties of the program (e.g., the program will not cause a memory access violation).
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi are closely related to mathematical logic and proof theory via the Curry–Howard isomorphism and they can be considered as the internal language of certain classes of categories.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] For example, the simply typed lambda calculus is the language of Cartesian closed categories (CCCs).
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Various typed lambda calculi have been studied.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] The simply typed lambda calculus has only one type constructor, the arrow $\to$ , and its only types are basic types and function types $\sigma \to \tau$ .
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] System T extends the simply typed lambda calculus with a type of natural numbers and higher-order primitive recursion; in this system all functions provably computable in Peano arithmetic are definable.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] System F allows polymorphism by using universal quantification over all types; from a logical perspective it can describe all functions that are provably total in second-order logic.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Lambda calculi with dependent types are the base of intuitionistic type theory, the calculus of constructions and the logical framework (LF), a pure lambda calculus with dependent types.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Based on work by Berardi on pure type systems, Henk Barendregt proposed the lambda cube to systematize the relations of pure typed lambda calculi (including simply typed lambda calculus, System F, LF and the calculus of constructions).
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Some typed lambda calculi introduce a notion of *subtyping*, i.e. if A is a subtype of B , then all terms of type A also have type B .
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi with subtyping are the simply typed lambda calculus with conjunctive types and System F<:.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] All the systems mentioned so far, with the exception of the untyped lambda calculus, are *strongly normalizing*: all computations terminate.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Therefore, they cannot describe all Turing-computable functions.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] As another consequence they are consistent as a logic, i.e. there are uninhabited types.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] There exist, however, typed lambda calculi that are not strongly normalizing.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] For example the dependently typed lambda calculus with a type of all types (Type : Type) is not normalizing due to Girard's paradox.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] This system is also the simplest pure type system, a formalism which generalizes the lambda cube.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Systems with explicit recursion combinators, such as Plotkin's "Programming language for Computable Functions" (PCF), are not normalizing, but they are not intended to be interpreted as a logic.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] Indeed, PCF is a prototypical, typed functional programming language, where types are used to ensure that programs are well-behaved but not necessarily that they are terminating.
[src:lambda-cube/typed-lambda-calculus] In computer programming, the routines (functions, procedures, methods) of strongly typed programming languages closely correspond to typed lambda expressions.
